SIMPLE: informer
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Informer
<hw>In*form"er</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n*f⟦ocir⟧rm"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[From <er>Inform</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One
who informs, animates, or inspires.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nature, <qex>informer</qex> of the poet's art.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who informs, or imparts knowledge or
news.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>One who informs a magistrate of
violations of law; one who informs against another for violation of some
law or penal statute.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Common informer</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>one who
habitually gives information of the violation of penal statutes, with a
view to a prosecution therefor.</cd> <au>Bouvier.</au>
<au>Wharton.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Informidable</ent>⟦br⟧
